<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="448" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1437,1144,2034]" pageId="0" pageNumber="448">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1362,1386]" pageId="0" pageNumber="448">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
The new species is similar with 
<taxonomicName authority="(Warren, 1900)" authorityName="Warren" authorityYear="1900" baseAuthorityName="Warren" baseAuthorityYear="1900" box="[655,1104,1362,1386]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Lissochlora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="448" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="purpureotincta">
<emphasis box="[655,940,1362,1386]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="448">Lissochlora purpureotincta</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Warren, W." box="[953,1097,1362,1386]" pageId="0" pageNumber="448" pagination="112 - 225" refId="ref2044" refString="Warren, W. (1900) New genera and species of American Drepanulidae, Thyrididae. Epiplemidae and Geometridae. Novitates zoologicae, 7, 112 - 225." type="journal article" year="1900">Warren, 1900</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
from Ecuador, differing in having broader wings, shorter palpi, and much longer male antennal rami. The socii are shorter in the male genitalia and the configuration of the distal costal process of valva is different in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Warren" baseAuthorityYear="1900" box="[777,960,1435,1458]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Lissochlora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="448" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="purpureotincta">
<emphasis box="[777,960,1435,1458]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="448">L. purpureotincta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Viidalepp &amp; Lindt, 2019" authorityName="Viidalepp &amp; Lindt" authorityYear="2019" box="[1010,1099,1434,1458]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Lissochlora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="448" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="klausi" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[1010,1099,1434,1458]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="448">L. klausi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1112,1171,1434,1458]" pageId="0" pageNumber="448">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1112,1171,1434,1458]" pageId="0" pageNumber="448" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(compare Figs 3 and 4).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="448" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1437,1144,2034]" pageId="0" pageNumber="448">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,340,1470,1494]" pageId="0" pageNumber="448">Description:</emphasis>
Wing span 
<quantity box="[465,539,1470,1494]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.1" pageId="0" pageNumber="448" unit="mm" value="21.0">21 mm</quantity>
in male, 
<quantity box="[637,751,1470,1494]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.45" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="2.4" pageId="0" pageNumber="448" unit="mm" value="24.5" valueMax="25.0" valueMin="24.0">24–25 mm</quantity>
in females (Fig. 1). The frons is brown with lower corners paler, the palpi are darker below, short and pointed in male but 
<quantity box="[785,868,1506,1530]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="0" pageNumber="448" unit="mm" value="0.6">0.6 mm</quantity>
long in females. Male antennae are bipectinate, the rami 
<quantity box="[207,302,1542,1566]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" pageId="0" pageNumber="448" unit="mm" value="0.45">0.45 mm</quantity>
long on the tenth segment. The hindtibial process is 
<quantity box="[869,951,1542,1566]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="0" pageNumber="448" unit="mm" value="0.6">0.6 mm</quantity>
long. The interantennal fillet is broad, white, the vertex green, a broad dark rosy line between. The metathorax is grey, the white blotch on tergite A1 is quadrangular, broader than long, edged red-brown, the dorsum of tergite A2 is green, without a blotch, the white blotch on the tergite A3 is large and edged red-brown; the dorsum of the fourth tergite is grey with a smaller white spot. The wings are green, the ante- and postmedian lines represented by pairs of brown and white vein-spots of equal size. The postmedial spots are white on the hindwing. The red-brown marginal line is bold, sometimes slightly lunulate, disrupted by pale spots on the veins; the fringe is white in its basal third, greyish distally, strongly chequered brownish against vein ends, retaining a row of slender, oval, white streaks.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1437,1144,2034]" pageId="0" pageNumber="448">
Male genitalia (Fig. 3): The uncus is sclerotised and conical with a stick-shaped apical process; the socii are broad at the base, slender at the apex; the process of the gnathos is spoon-shaped but slender; the costa of the valva is broad, broader than the valvula, produced leg-shaped rather than bifid beyond the costal edge as in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Warren" baseAuthorityYear="1900" box="[1135,1322,1902,1926]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Lissochlora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="448" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="purpureotincta">
<emphasis box="[1135,1150,1903,1926]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="448">L</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1163,1322,1903,1926]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="448">purpureotincta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but nearer to the valvula. The tip of the costa is not upcurved in other members of the 
<taxonomicName box="[975,1120,1938,1962]" class="Insecta" family="Geometridae" genus="Lissochlora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="448" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albociliaia">
<emphasis box="[975,1120,1938,1962]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="448">L. albociliaia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group. The coremata hairscales are blackish. The last abdominal sternite is distally bilobed, twice broader than long. The aedeagus is slender. Female genitalia (Fig. 5): The ductus bursae is as long as the corpus bursae, the signum is present.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1113,153,177]" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,153,249]" box="[199,1113,153,177]" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,483,153,177]" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">Biology and distribution.</emphasis>
The species inhabits tropical rainforests in French Guiana.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="449" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,153,249]" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,410,189,213]" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">Derivatio nominis.</emphasis>
The new species is named after Klaus, the baby boy in the family of the first author’s grandson Erki Viidalepp.
</paragraph>
